(firstQuint)Comparison of Autologous Serum and Umbilical Cord Serum Eyedrops for Dry Eye Syndrome.

 Ninety-two eyes of 48 patients with severe dry eye syndrome (34 eyes of 17 patients with Sjogren's syndrome and 58 eyes of 31 patients with non-Sjogren's syndrome) were treated with either 20% autologous serum (41 eyes of 21 patients) or umbilical cord serum eyedrops (51 eyes of 27 patients).

 Symptom scoring, corneal sensitivity test, tear film break-up time (BUT), Schirmer test, tear clearance rate (TCR), corneal fluorescein staining, and conjunctival impression cytology were performed before and 1 month and 2 months after treatment.

